NeuralNetwork Project by Hari¶

DOMAIN: Electronics and Telecommunication
CONTEXT: A communications equipment manufacturing company has a product which is responsible for emitting informative signals. Company wants to build a machine learning model which can help the company to predict the equipments signal quality using various parameters.
DATA DESCRIPTION:
The data set contains information on various signal tests performed:

  1. Parameters: Various measurable signal parameters.
  2. Signal_Quality: Final signal strength or quality
    PROJECT OBJECTIVE: To build a classifier which can use the given parameters to determine the signal strength or quality

def nulsCount(df):
    """summarise missing/unexpected values"""
    
    d2=pd.DataFrame(columns=["NULL","NAN","BLANKS","UNEXP"])
    try:
        d2["NULL"] = df.isnull().sum().astype('uint32') # check for null values
        d2["NAN"]=df.isna().sum().astype('uint32') # check for NaN
        d2["BLANKS"]=df.isin([""," "]).sum().astype('uint32') # check for blanks
        d2["UNEXP"]=df.isin(["-","?",".","NA","N/A","Unknown"]).sum().astype('uint32') # check for other unexpected values
    except:
        pass
    d2=d2.loc[(d2["NULL"]!=0) | (d2["NAN"]!=0) | (d2["BLANKS"]!=0) | (d2["UNEXP"]!=0)] # shortlist for the missing values
    
    # convert to percentages
    d2["NULL %"] = d2["NULL"].mul(100/df.shape[0]).round(2)
    d2["NAN %"] = d2["NAN"].mul(100/df.shape[0]).round(2)
    d2["BLANKS %"] = d2["BLANKS"].mul(100/df.shape[0]).round(2)
    d2["UNEXP %"] = d2["UNEXP"].mul(100/df.shape[0]).round(2)
    
    # rearrange
    d2=d2[["NULL","NULL %","NAN","NAN %","BLANKS","BLANKS %","UNEXP","UNEXP %"]]
    
    if d2.shape[0]==0:
        return
    else:     
        return d2

# adding matplotlib graphs for html saving
def tensorPlot(log):
    fig=plt.figure()
    x=len(log.history.get('loss'))

    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.plot(np.arange(x), log.history.get('loss'), color='b', label="test_loss")
    plt.plot(np.arange(x), log.history.get('val_loss'), color='r', label="val_loss")
    plt.plot()
    plt.legend()

    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.plot(np.arange(x), log.history.get('accuracy'), color='b', label="test_accuracy")
    plt.plot(np.arange(x), log.history.get('val_accuracy'), color='r', label="val_accuracy")
    plt.plot()
    plt.legend()
    
    fig.show()

def heatmp(x,y,z):
    df=pd.DataFrame(z,columns=y,index=y)
    fig=plt.figure()
    plt.plot()
    sns.heatmap(df,annot=True,fmt='d',cmap='GnBu')
    fig.show()
In [32]:
# classification metrics report
def evalNN(Y_test,prediction):
    pred = (prediction>0.5)
    yt = (Y_test>0.5)
    pred = np.argmax(pred,axis=1)
    yt = np.argmax(yt,axis=1)

    classes=list(np.unique(yt))
    classes.extend(np.unique(pred))
    classes=np.unique(classes)
    
    z=np.array(pd.DataFrame(metrics.confusion_matrix(yt,pred)))

    heatmp(classes,classes,z)

    print("CLASSIFICATION REPORT\n",metrics.classification_report(yt, pred, digits=3))
In [33]:
# lets define a network function
def NNf(data,params,epochs,verbose=False):

    np.random.seed(129)
    tf.random.set_seed(129)

    [X_train,Y_train,X_test,Y_test]=data
    [hl,hln,lr,lmbda,bn,do] = params

    # initiate network
    NN = Sequential()
    init = tf.keras.initializers.GlorotNormal(seed=129)
    NN.add(Dense(len(X_train[0]), input_shape = (len(X_train[0]),), activation = 'relu',kernel_initializer=init))
    for i in range(hl):
        if bn:
            NN.add(BatchNormalization())
        NN.add(Dropout(do))
        NN.add(Dense(hln, activation="relu",kernel_initializer=init))
    if bn:
        NN.add(BatchNormalization())
    NN.add(Dropout(do))
    NN.add(Dense(len(Y_train[0]), activation="softmax",kernel_initializer=init,
                    kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(lmbda)))

    # Compile the model
    # sgd = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = lr, decay=1e-6)
    sgd = optimizers.RMSprop(learning_rate=lr,rho=0.9, momentum=0.1, epsilon=1e-07)

    NN.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"], optimizer=sgd)

    # Fit the model
    log=NN.fit(x=X_train, y=Y_train, batch_size=50, epochs=epochs,
               validation_data=(X_test, Y_test),verbose=0)

    # evaluate the model
    [loss,accuracy] = NN.evaluate(X_test, Y_test,verbose=0)
    if verbose:
        # review model architecture
        display(NN.summary())
        # display the loss & accuracy progress
        tensorPlot(log)
        print("Loss     :%.6f"%loss)
        print("Accuracy :%.6f"%accuracy)

        prediction = NN.predict(X_test)
        evalNN(Y_test,prediction)

    p_acc,p_epoch = np.max(log.history.get('val_accuracy')),np.argmax(log.history.get('val_accuracy'))

    return p_acc,p_epoch

In [39]:
%%time
# perform random grid search
epochs = 50
nSearch = 10
for niter,iter in enumerate(np.random.randint(0,len(pgrid),nSearch)):
    params = pgrid[iter][:-1]
    if pgrid[iter][-1] == 'mima':
        data = [X_tr_mima,Y_train,X_te_mima,Y_test]
    elif pgrid[iter][-1] == 'std':
        data = [X_tr_std,Y_train,X_te_std,Y_test]

    p_acc,p_epoch = NNf(data,params,epochs,verbose = False)

    storage = pgrid[iter].copy()
    storage.append(p_acc)
    storage.append(p_epoch)
    file = open("NN_tuning.har",'ab')
    pickle.dump(storage,file)
    file.close()

with 1931 learnable paramters, the base model gave a peak accuracy 0.6029 at 5th epoch, beyond which it diverged much
on the other hand the recent chosen network, with 19096 learnable parameters, it gave an accuracy of 0.6299 at 23rd epoch
It could also be noted that the effective accuracy drops down to just 0.402 based on the confusion matrix
though the outcome is not an appreciable accuracy, the validation accuracy has not departed from the training accuracy, indicating better learning than the base model where it showed signs of over fitting at a much earlier epoch.
This is an indication of a better optimised network.
Further working on the feature engineering and feature selection would significantly improve the model performance

In principle the 2 models differet in the kinds of layers used.
Plain Linear layer with RELU activations were the style of base model (obviously with Softmax output layer)
Whereas the final model consists of batch normalisation layer to adjust for incoming data ranges, Dropout layer to emulate missing values in the records (to improve generalization of the model, and to avoid overfitting), followed by regular linear layers and ending with softmax classification output
The final model is an outcome of rigorous hypertuning/search for the available dataset patterns.
In terms of performance / learning progress the base model plunged the training losses easily below 0.8 but failed to generalize when validated. as a result of lower loss, the backpropagation would have hardly changed the weights.
Whereas, the final model was having higher losses owing to normalization, this enabled the model to continously learn for further epochs than the base model.

Part Two¶

DOMAIN: Autonomous Vehicles
CONTEXT: A Recognising multi-digit numbers in photographs captured at street level is an important component of modern-day map making. A classic example of a corpus of such street-level photographs is Googles Street View imagery composed of hundreds of millions of geo-located 360-degree panoramic images. The ability to automatically transcribe an address number from a geo-located patch of pixels and associate the transcribed number with a known street address helps pinpoint, with a high degree of accuracy, the location of the building it represents. More broadly, recognising numbers in photographs is a problem of interest to the optical character recognition community.
While OCR on constrained domains like document processing is well studied, arbitrary multi-character text recognition in photographs is still highly challenging. This difficulty arises due to the wide variability in the visual appearance of text in the wild on account of a large range of fonts, colours, styles, orientations, and character arrangements.
The recognition problem is further complicated by environmental factors such as lighting, shadows, specularity, and occlusions as well as by image acquisition factors such as resolution, motion, and focus blurs. In this project, we will use the dataset with images centred around a single digit (many of the images do contain some distractors at the sides). Although we are taking a sample of the data which is simpler, it is more complex than MNIST because of the distractors.
DATA DESCRIPTION: The SVHN is a real-world image dataset for developing machine learning and object recognition algorithms with the minimal requirement on data formatting but comes from a significantly harder, unsolved, real-world problem (recognising digits and numbers in natural scene images). SVHN is obtained from house numbers in Google Street View images. Where the labels for each of this image are the prominent number in that image i.e. 2,6,7 and 4 respectively. The dataset has been provided in the form of h5py files. You can read about this file format here:
http://docs.h5py.org/en/stable/high/dataset.html
Acknowledgement: Yuval Netzer, Tao Wang, Adam Coates, Alessandro Bissacco, Bo Wu, Andrew Y. Ng
Reading Digits in Natural Images with Unsupervised Feature Learning NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning and Unsupervised Feature Learning 2011.
http://ufldl.stanford.edu/housenumbers as the URL for this site.
PROJECT OBJECTIVE: To build a digit classifier on the SVHN (Street View Housing Number) dataset.

# classification metrics report
def evalNN(Y_test,prediction):
    pred = (prediction>0.5)
    yt = (Y_test>0.5)
    pred = np.argmax(pred,axis=1)
    yt = np.argmax(yt,axis=1)

    classes=list(np.unique(yt))
    classes.extend(np.unique(pred))
    classes=np.unique(classes)
    
    z=np.array(pd.DataFrame(metrics.confusion_matrix(yt,pred)))
    
    heatmp(classes,classes,z)
    
    print("CLASSIFICATION REPORT\n",metrics.classification_report(yt, pred, digits=3))
In [60]:
# lets define a network function
def NNimg(data,params,epochs,verbose=False):

    np.random.seed(129)
    tf.random.set_seed(129)

    [X_train,Y_train,X_test,Y_test]=data
    [hl,hln,lr,lmbda,do] = params

    # initiate network
    NN = Sequential()
    init = tf.keras.initializers.GlorotNormal(seed=129)
    NN.add(Dense(len(X_train[0]), input_shape = (len(X_train[0]),), activation = 'relu',kernel_initializer=init))
    for i in range(hl):
        NN.add(BatchNormalization())
        NN.add(Dropout(do))
        NN.add(Dense(hln, activation="relu",kernel_initializer=init))
    NN.add(BatchNormalization())
    NN.add(Dropout(do))
    NN.add(Dense(len(Y_train[0]), activation="softmax",kernel_initializer=init,
                    kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(lmbda)))

    # Compile the model
    # sgd = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = lr, decay=1e-6)
    sgd = optimizers.RMSprop(learning_rate=lr,rho=0.9, momentum=0.1, epsilon=1e-07)

    NN.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"], optimizer=sgd)

    # Fit the model
    log=NN.fit(x=X_train, y=Y_train, batch_size=50, epochs=epochs,
               validation_data=(X_test, Y_test),verbose=0)

    # evaluate the model
    [loss,accuracy] = NN.evaluate(X_test, Y_test,verbose=0)
    if verbose:
        # review model architecture
        display(NN.summary())
        # display the loss & accuracy progress
        tensorPlot(log)
        print("Loss     :%.6f"%loss)
        print("Accuracy :%.6f"%accuracy)

        prediction = NN.predict(X_test)
        evalNN(Y_test,prediction)
        
    p_acc,p_epoch = np.max(log.history.get('val_accuracy')),np.argmax(log.history.get('val_accuracy'))

    return p_acc,p_epoch

%%time
# perform random grid search
epochs = 20
nSearch = 2
data = [h5X_train,h5Y_train,h5X_test,h5Y_test]
for niter,iter in enumerate(np.random.randint(0,len(pgrid),nSearch)):
    params = pgrid[iter]
    p_acc,p_epoch = NNimg(data,params,epochs,verbose = False)

    storage = pgrid[iter].copy()
    storage.append(p_acc)
    storage.append(p_epoch)
    file = open("NN_img_tuning.har",'ab')
    pickle.dump(storage,file)
    file.close()

    print("iter %d / %d"%(niter+1,nSearch))
    print(p_acc,p_epoch)
    print("="*50)
